{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 5: Information Systems in Business\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 5 delves into the various types of information systems used in business environments, their roles, and their impact on organizational efficiency and decision-making. The chapter covers Transaction Processing Systems (TPS), Enterprise Resource Planning Systems (ERPS), Decision Support Systems (DSS), and Management Information Systems (MIS). It also discusses the sources of management information, both internal and external, and their applications at different management levels. Key examples include Moffat Co's decision to invest in an ERPS and the implementation of EPOS and ERPS in XYZ Stores. The chapter emphasizes the importance of accurate and timely information for strategic, tactical, and operational planning and control.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The chapter is highly significant due to its comprehensive coverage of essential information systems that are critical for business operations and decision-making.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Transaction Processing Systems (TPS) are fundamental for operational efficiency.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"A Transaction Processing System (TPS) is responsible for capturing and processing data related to business transactions. It is used by operational staff to capture data and make processes more efficient, thereby improving the accuracy and timeliness of information. TPS data is primarily high-frequency and short-term, providing detailed and short-term information for operational planning and control [Data: Concepts (21); Relationships (34)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Enterprise Resource Planning Systems (ERPS) integrate information across an organization.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Enterprise Resource Planning System (ERPS) is a comprehensive software system designed to facilitate a seamless flow of information across an entire organization. By utilizing a single database, it ensures that various programs used by different departments can access and share data efficiently. ERPS supports multiple simultaneous users, providing real-time information and includes essential modules for accounting, inventory control, and other critical business processes [Data: Concepts (1566); Relationships (35, 82, 43)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Decision Support Systems (DSS) aid in tactical decision-making.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"A Decision Support System (DSS) is designed to support the tactical level of an organization by aiding managers in their decision-making processes. It provides relevant data, analytical tools, and models that help in analyzing information and exploring 'what-if' scenarios and outcomes based on various input variables. By offering these capabilities, a DSS assists managers in making informed and effective decisions [Data: Concepts (23); Relationships (42, 41)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Internal and external sources of management information serve different purposes.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Internal sources of management information include systems like accounting, inventory, payroll, purchase processing, and sales processing systems. These systems provide detailed information on costs, revenues, inventory movements, employee costs, supplier information, customer purchases, and customer satisfaction. External sources include market research, competitor pricing, government statistics, country reports, business directories, and trade magazines. These sources provide primary and secondary data tailored to an organization's needs and are used for strategic purposes [Data: Concepts (14, 15); Relationships (6, 13)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Moffat Co's decision to invest in an ERPS highlights the strategic importance of integrated information systems.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Moffat Co, which supplies and fits tyres and exhaust pipes and services motor vehicles at 30 locations, is considering investing in an ERPS to improve decision-making and information flow across the organization. This decision underscores the strategic importance of having an integrated system that can provide real-time, accurate information to support long-term business planning and decision-making [Data: Concepts (2019); Relationships (1481, 1806, 1807, 1808)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Implementation of EPOS and ERPS in XYZ Stores demonstrates operational improvements.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"XYZ Stores operates a chain of 10 convenience stores with basic information systems. The case involves the implementation and evaluation of Electronic Point of Sale (EPOS) and Enterprise Resource Planning Systems (ERPS) to improve operational efficiency. The integration of these systems helps manage sales transactions and inventory control, providing real-time data and enhancing overall operational efficiency [Data: Concepts (1564); Relationships (1477, 1478)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Different levels of management use information for control purposes.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Strategic managers use high-level information for long-term planning and control, tactical managers use detailed internal information for efficient operation, and operational managers use detailed transactional information from sub-systems. This hierarchical use of information ensures that each level of management has the appropriate data to make informed decisions and maintain control over their respective areas [Data: Concepts (16); Relationships (23, 21, 22)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Expected present value of profits with and without market research.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The expected present value of profits with market research is calculated by considering the probability of success and failure, and the associated profits and losses. The formula used is: EV = (Probability of Success * Profit) + (Probability of Failure * Loss). This is compared to the expected present value of profits without market research to determine the value of market research. The value of imperfect information is the difference between these two expected values, quantifying the benefit of having additional, albeit imperfect, information [Data: Concepts (795, 796, 797); Relationships (648, 649, 650)].\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery within a textbook. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., concepts, methodologies, quizzes, examples, cases) within a chapter of a textbook.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a chapter, given a list of concepts, methodologies, formulas and examples that belong to the chapter as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform educators and students about the chapter's content and its key components. The content of this report includes an overview of the chapter's key entities, their definitions, interrelations, and noteworthy details.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: Chapter title - the title is given in the textbook in the format 'Chapter X: title'\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary that outlines the chapter's structure and the main learning outcomes. Focus on the key concepts as mentioned in the learning outcomes, their relevant examples, formulas, and methodologies, and how these elements are related to each other.\n- IMPACT SEVERITY RATING: a float score between 0-10 that represents the significance of the chapter's content. This score reflects the importance and relevance of the chapter's material in the context of the textbook.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the significance rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the chapter. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format:\n    {{\n        \"title\": <report_title>,\n        \"summary\": <executive_summary>,\n        \"rating\": <impact_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": <rating_explanation>,\n        \"findings\": [\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_1_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_1_explanation>\n            }},\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_2_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n21,\"\"\"TRANSACTION PROCESSING SYSTEM (TPS)\"\"\",\"A Transaction Processing System (TPS) is responsible for capturing and processing data related to business transactions. It is a type of information system used by operational staff to capture data and make processes more efficient, thereby improving the accuracy and timeliness of information. TPS data is primarily high-frequency and short-term. As an operational information system, TPS processes transaction-based data, providing detailed and short-term information for operational planning and control.\",7\n1566,\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"The Enterprise Resource Planning System (ERPS) is a comprehensive software system designed to facilitate a seamless flow of information across an entire organization. By utilizing a single database, it ensures that various programs used by different departments can access and share data efficiently. ERPS is an integrated information system that supports multiple simultaneous users, providing real-time information. It includes essential modules for accounting, inventory control, and other critical business processes, thereby enhancing the overall operational efficiency of the organization.\",8\n23,\"\"\"DECISION SUPPORT SYSTEM (DSS)\"\"\",\"A Decision Support System (DSS) is a type of information system designed to support the tactical level of an organization by aiding managers in their decision-making processes. It provides relevant data, analytical tools, and models that help in analyzing information and exploring 'what-if' scenarios and outcomes based on various input variables. By offering these capabilities, a DSS assists managers in making informed and effective decisions.\",5\n15,\"\"\"EXTERNAL SOURCES OF MANAGEMENT INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"External sources of management information are used for strategic purposes and include primary information tailored to an organization's needs, such as market research and competitor pricing, and secondary information produced for general use, such as government statistics, country reports, business directories, and trade magazines.\"\"\",7\n16,\"\"\"USE OF INFORMATION IN CONTROL\"\"\",\"\"\"Different levels of management use information for control purposes: strategic managers use high-level information for long-term planning and control, tactical managers use detailed internal information for efficient operation, and operational managers use detailed transactional information from sub-systems.\"\"\",6\n14,\"\"\"INTERNAL SOURCES OF MANAGEMENT INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Internal sources of management information include the accounting system, inventory system, payroll system, purchase processing system, sales processing system, and qualitative information systems. These systems provide detailed information on costs, revenues, inventory movements, employee costs, supplier information, customer purchases, and customer satisfaction.\"\"\",7\n2019,\"\"\"MOFFAT CO'S DECISION TO INVEST IN AN ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Moffat Co, which supplies and fits tyres and exhaust pipes and services motor vehicles at 30 locations, is considering investing in an enterprise resource planning system (ERPS) to improve decision-making and information flow across the organization.\"\"\",4\n1564,\"\"\"IMPLEMENTATION AND EVALUATION OF EPOS AND ERPS IN XYZ STORES\"\"\",\"\"\"IMPLEMENTATION AND EVALUATION OF EPOS AND ERPS IN XYZ STORES\"\"\n\nXYZ Stores operates a chain of 10 convenience stores with basic information systems. The case involves the implementation and evaluation of Electronic Point of Sale (EPOS) and Enterprise Resource Planning Systems (ERPS) to improve operational efficiency.\",3\n20,\"\"\"INFORMATION SYSTEMS\"\"\",\"Information Systems are systems that monitor and manage the activities and transactions of an organization, encompassing management-level, operational-level, knowledge-level, and strategic-level systems. The four main types of information systems that support different levels of an organization include: Executive Information System (EIS) for strategic purposes, Decision Support System (DSS) and Management Information System (MIS) for tactical purposes, and Transaction Processing System (TPS) for operational purposes. Additionally, using a software package that integrates with the company's systems is recommended for managing a rolling budget. This approach ensures unified budgeting data, easy access, and updates by multiple users, although it may come at a substantial cost and require user support and training.\",3\n2020,\"\"\"STRATEGIC INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Strategic information is required by management to take a longer-term view of the business and assess its performance over time. It is holistic and summary in nature and used for activities like SWOT analysis and assessing new service developments or potential acquisitions.\"\"\",2\n2021,\"\"\"TACTICAL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Tactical information facilitates management planning and control for shorter time periods than strategic information. It relates to specific actions to achieve certain goals, such as opening new outlets or employing additional supervisors.\"\"\",2\n2022,\"\"\"OPERATIONAL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Operational information relates to short time scales and is used for immediate actions by day-to-day management. It includes data on customer sales, vehicles serviced, and complaints received, and helps determine staffing needs and training requirements.\"\"\",2\n40,\"\"\"ELECTRONIC DATA INTERCHANGE (EDI)\"\"\",\"Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) is a system that enables the supermarket's system to communicate with the suppliers' systems, facilitating transactions such as placing orders, receiving goods, and making payments.\",2\n39,\"\"\"ELECTRONIC POINT OF SALE (EPOS)\"\"\",\"Electronic Point of Sale (EPOS) is a computerized system used to record sales transactions. It utilizes bar code readers to capture details of each sale and can be linked to other systems for real-time data processing and inventory management. In a supermarket setting, the Transaction Processing System (TPS) may include an EPOS system, where goods are scanned by the cashier using a bar-code reader when the customer is checking out.\",2\n31,\"\"\"MARKET RESEARCH\"\"\",\"\"\"Market research is an external source of management information that provides primary data tailored to an organization's needs, such as customer preferences and market trends.\"\"\",2\n19,\"\"\"OPERATIONAL PLANNING AND CONTROL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Operational planning requires transaction-based data, which is almost entirely internal and covers short-term periods. Examples include variances, receivables/payables levels, payroll details, customer complaints, and output records.\"\"\",2\n18,\"\"\"TACTICAL PLANNING AND CONTROL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Information for tactical planning contains detailed internal information, is provided regularly, and includes forecasts up to 12 months. Examples include annual budgets, sales analysis by product/customer/location, inventory levels, and cash flow projections.\"\"\",3\n25,\"\"\"ACCOUNTING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"The accounting system is an internal source of management information that records financial transactions and provides data on costs, revenues, and financial performance.\"\"\",1\n37,\"\"\"BATCH PROCESSING\"\"\",\"\"\"Batch processing is an approach where individual transactions of the same type are collected into batches and stored for later input to the computer. Processing proceeds in discrete runs, making it easier to control as data can be checked and validated before processing.\"\"\",1\n35,\"\"\"BUSINESS DIRECTORIES\"\"\",\"\"\"Business directories are an external source of management information that provides secondary data on companies, including contact information and business profiles.\"\"\",1\n32,\"\"\"COMPETITOR PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Competitor pricing is an external source of management information that provides primary data on the pricing strategies of competitors.\"\"\",1\n34,\"\"\"COUNTRY REPORTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Country reports are an external source of management information that provides secondary data on the economic, political, and social conditions of different countries.\"\"\",1\n24,\"\"\"MANAGEMENT INFORMATION SYSTEM (MIS)\"\"\",\"Management Information System (MIS) is a tactical information system that provides regular reports and summaries of data to help managers with planning, controlling, and decision-making. It is a type of information system that converts data from internal and external sources into information used by management at all levels and across all functions to make timely and effective decisions.\",3\n33,\"\"\"GOVERNMENT STATISTICS\"\"\",\"\"\"Government statistics are an external source of management information that provides secondary data produced for general use, such as economic indicators and demographic data.\"\"\",1\n36,\"\"\"TRADE MAGAZINES\"\"\",\"\"\"Trade magazines are an external source of management information that provides secondary data on industry trends, news, and developments.\"\"\",1\n26,\"\"\"INVENTORY SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"The inventory system is an internal source of management information that tracks inventory levels, movements, and valuations.\"\"\",1\n27,\"\"\"PAYROLL SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"The payroll system is an internal source of management information that manages employee compensation, benefits, and related costs.\"\"\",1\n28,\"\"\"PURCHASE PROCESSING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"The purchase processing system is an internal source of management information that handles procurement activities, supplier information, and purchase orders.\"\"\",1\n29,\"\"\"SALES PROCESSING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"The sales processing system is an internal source of management information that manages customer orders, sales transactions, and customer information.\"\"\",1\n30,\"\"\"QUALITATIVE INFORMATION SYSTEMS\"\"\",\"\"\"Qualitative information systems are internal sources of management information that provide non-quantitative data, such as customer satisfaction and employee feedback.\"\"\",1\n43,\"\"\"OPERATIONAL LEVEL\"\"\",\"\"\"The operational level of an organization involves day-to-day activities and decision-making by operational staff to ensure efficient and effective execution of tasks.\"\"\",1\n38,\"\"\"REAL-TIME PROCESSING\"\"\",\"\"\"Real-time processing is an approach where transactions are processed immediately as they occur, ensuring that information in the system is always up-to-date. However, it can be challenging to control, and the risk of errors is greater.\"\"\",1\n17,\"\"\"STRATEGIC PLANNING AND CONTROL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Information for strategic planning addresses high-level objectives, includes external information, is often ad hoc, and contains long-term forecasts. Examples include economic and market forecasts, competitor analysis, profits by business segment, and investment appraisal.\"\"\",2\n22,\"\"\"EXECUTIVE INFORMATION SYSTEM (EIS)\"\"\",\"An Executive Information System (EIS) is a strategic information system designed to provide high-level, summarized information to senior executives within an organization. It often includes features such as data visualizations and reporting tools, which aid in long-term planning and decision-making. The primary purpose of an EIS is to support executives by delivering critical information in a concise and accessible format, enabling them to make informed strategic decisions.\",5\n1567,\"\"\"REPORTING PROGRAMME\"\"\",\"\"\"A reporting programme is a software tool that analyzes data from the ERPS database and provides reports, summaries, and data visualizations such as bar charts, line charts, and pie charts. It includes a 'drill down' facility for detailed analysis and allows managers to design their own reports.\"\"\",2\n46,\"\"\"CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTORS (CSFS)\"\"\",\"\"\"Critical Success Factors (CSFs) are the essential areas of activity that must be performed well for an organization to achieve its mission and objectives.\"\"\",1\n47,\"\"\"DATA ANALYSIS TOOLS\"\"\",\"\"\"Data analysis tools are software applications and methodologies used to analyze data, identify patterns, and support decision-making processes.\"\"\",1\n42,\"\"\"TACTICAL LEVEL\"\"\",\"\"\"The tactical level of an organization involves short- to medium-term planning and decision-making by middle managers to implement strategies and achieve specific objectives.\"\"\",1\n44,\"\"\"INTERNAL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Internal information refers to data generated within an organization, such as financial records, employee data, and internal reports.\"\"\",1\n45,\"\"\"EXTERNAL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"External information refers to data obtained from outside an organization, such as market trends, competitor analysis, and regulatory requirements.\"\"\",1\n41,\"\"\"QUIZ ON INFORMATION SYSTEMS\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ ON INFORMATION SYSTEMS\"\" is a quiz that involves suggesting examples of information required from an information system for a market trader working in a fruit market and a materials purchasing department in a factory.\",3\n795,\"\"\"EXPECTED PRESENT VALUE OF PROFITS WITH MARKET RESEARCH\"\"\",\"\"\"The expected present value of profits with market research is calculated by considering the probability of success and failure, and the associated profits and losses. The formula used is: EV = (Probability of Success * Profit) + (Probability of Failure * Loss).\"\"\",2\n796,\"\"\"EXPECTED PRESENT VALUE OF PROFITS WITHOUT MARKET RESEARCH\"\"\",\"\"\"The expected present value of profits without market research is calculated by considering the probability of success and failure, and the associated profits and losses. The formula used is: EV = (Probability of Success * Profit) + (Probability of Failure * Loss).\"\"\",3\n797,\"\"\"VALUE OF IMPERFECT INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"The value of imperfect information is the difference between the expected value if market research is commissioned and the expected value if it is not. It quantifies the benefit of having additional information that is not perfect but still useful.\"\"\",2\n1231,\"\"\"INFORMATION SYSTEMS QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"A quiz that tests knowledge on the types of information systems that monitor elementary activities and transactions of organizations.\"\"\",1\n50,\"\"\"MARKET TRADER\"\"\",\"\"\"A market trader is an individual who sells goods, typically in a market setting, and requires information on inventory, sales, and market trends to operate effectively.\"\"\",1\n51,\"\"\"MATERIALS PURCHASING DEPARTMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The materials purchasing department in a factory is responsible for procuring raw materials and supplies needed for production, requiring information on inventory levels, supplier performance, and order status.\"\"\",1\n48,\"\"\"BAR-CODE READER\"\"\",\"\"\"A bar-code reader is a device used to scan and read barcodes, typically used in retail environments to track inventory and process sales transactions.\"\"\",1\n49,\"\"\"SUPPLIERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Suppliers are external entities that provide goods or services to an organization, playing a crucial role in the supply chain.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n35,\"\"\"TRANSACTION PROCESSING SYSTEM (TPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"An Enterprise Resource Planning System (ERPS) is different from a Transaction Processing System (TPS), which captures and processes data.\"\"\",15\n82,\"\"\"CUSTOMER RELATIONSHIP MANAGEMENT SYSTEM (CRM)\"\"\",\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"An Enterprise Resource Planning System (ERPS) is different from a Customer Relationship Management System (CRM), which manages customer interactions.\"\"\",14\n43,\"\"\"DECISION SUPPORT SYSTEM (DSS)\"\"\",\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"An Enterprise Resource Planning System (ERPS) is different from a Decision Support System (DSS), which provides 'what-if' scenarios.\"\"\",13\n13,\"\"\"EXTERNAL SOURCES OF MANAGEMENT INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"USE OF INFORMATION IN CONTROL\"\"\",\"\"\"External sources of management information are primarily used for strategic control purposes.\"\"\",13\n6,\"\"\"INTERNAL SOURCES OF MANAGEMENT INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"USE OF INFORMATION IN CONTROL\"\"\",\"\"\"Internal sources of management information provide the detailed data needed for tactical and operational control purposes.\"\"\",13\n1481,\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"MOFFAT CO'S DECISION TO INVEST IN AN ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Moffat Co's decision to invest in an ERPS is directly related to the features and advantages of an Enterprise Resource Planning System.\"\"\",12\n1477,\"\"\"IMPLEMENTATION AND EVALUATION OF EPOS AND ERPS IN XYZ STORES\"\"\",\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Implementation and Evaluation of EPOS and ERPS in XYZ Stores involves the integration of an Enterprise Resource Planning System (ERPS) to manage sales transactions and inventory control.\"\"\",11\n29,\"\"\"INFORMATION SYSTEMS\"\"\",\"\"\"ROLLING BUDGET APPROACH\"\"\",\"\"\"Integrated information systems are recommended for managing a rolling budget approach.\"\"\",11\n1482,\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"STRATEGIC INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"An ERPS provides strategic information needed for long-term business planning and decision-making.\"\"\",10\n1483,\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"TACTICAL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"An ERPS provides tactical information needed for short-term planning and control.\"\"\",10\n1484,\"\"\"ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM (ERPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"OPERATIONAL INFORMATION\"\"\",\"\"\"An ERPS provides operational information needed for day-to-day management decisions.\"\"\",10\n33,\"\"\"TRANSACTION PROCESSING SYSTEM (TPS)\"\"\",\"\"\"ELECTRONIC DATA INTERCHANGE (EDI)\"\"\",\"\"\"Tran